		<br>
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr><td><P>

 Hey Milo,<P>

 I have a small favor to ask of you. And no, it's not about employment at Verant, I already have applied several times (can you blame me?They're great and they're local). Would you send me a copy of the cover letter that got you hired at your current job? I feel I am good enough to work in game development, so I think the problem must be in how I am selling myself. Oh, and feel free to remove any personal information, I am only interested in the style one uses to get an interview as an artist at an online games company.<P>

 Thanks and I hope you reply to this,

 Kalanien<BR>
 10th level bard<BR>
 Innoruk<BR>
 *account canceled due to lack of money and a real job...

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   I have no such letter.  I posted a brief synopsis of my work history a
while
ago, so I won't go into detail here (check the archives, if you're
interested),
but basically, I got my foot in the door about nine years ago, and I've had
some kind of history with many of my superiors ever since that time (I knew
and worked with both John Smedley and Brad McQuaid -- Verant's CEO
and VP, respectively -- many years before EverQuest was even conceived).
If you've got to sell yourself, then I guess you've got to do it, but I
prefer to
shoot for jobs where someone I know and respect is familiar with my work.
I can't help you, here, my friend.  Sorry.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 Please excuse the vehemence of my previous email, but your offhanded way
of dismissing poor spelling and grammar by programmers got me riled.<P>

 Unfortunately, you still make excuses for poor workmanship, quibbling
about whether "disinterest and sloth aren't the same thing."  Just how does disinterest in doing something, and thereby not making the effort to do it correctly, differ substantially from laziness in respect to that task?  To quote my previous email, "to put it another way, the authors just DON'T
CARE!"<P>

  Disinterest and not caring, to me, seem much the same.<P>

 You appear to be quite talented at your modeling, yet you still
demonstrate a well-developed knowledge and skill with the written language.  Not only
that, but you repeatedly correct poor spelling and grammar from the people who
send you mail.  It seems to me that, in principle if not in fact, you should be demanding the same standards of your coworkers that you impose on yourself
and expect from your correspondents, not defending your coworkers'
transgressions.<P>

  Otherwise, your critiques of correspondents are baseless.  Who is to say
these same people you criticize so sharply are not talented experts in their
chosen fields who are just "disinterested" in spelling and grammar?<P>

 Sincerely,<BR>
 Mike Groman

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   "Disinterest and not caring, to me, seem much the same."  There's the big
hole in your argument -- your definition of laziness, i.e. "not caring."<P>

When
I spend two hours washing my car, I don't bother putting it on a lift or on
ramps so I can clean the undercarriage, because I really don't care how
dirty it looks under there.  Does that make me lazy?  If I'm driving on a
quiet street behind some guy who chucks a candy bar wrapper out his
window, I'm not going to stop to clean up his garbage. Like I care about
some little piece of paper in the road.  Am I lazy?  Say a major election is
coming up, and the candidates are faceless crowd-pleasers who pander to
the concerns of the domesticated proletariat.  I don't bother going to the
polls to vote, because neither politician interests me, and because the
sway of the masses is going to override my own interests, anyway.  Does
this mean that I'm lazy, or is more accurate to say that I don't give a rat
fart who wins?<P>

   I remember many a night during my high school days, when I elected to
spend my time doing something that I found much more interesting (usually
computer related -- my father sometimes called me "Computerhead"),
rather than my homework.  Since I was doing something, how could I have
been called slothful?  Were I slothful, I'd have done nothing at all.  I'd
have gone and watched television, or played video games, or chatted with
my friends on the telephone -- something that required little or no mental
or physical effort.<P>

   Your definition of laziness sucks.  It is entirely possible for someone
to
be lazy about something that interests him/her -- for example, someone
who *does* care who wins an election, but who is too indolent to go to a
poll booth.  In my experience, many (i.e. not all, so calm down, everyone)
high school and college instructors are very good at having definitions of
laziness that are just as sucky as yours; have you considered a job as a
teacher?<P>

   As for your observation that it isn't fair for me to excuse the
grammatical
errors of my co-workers while I chastise readers of this column, you are
correct in any situation in which I know that the person who makes the
mistakes is a highly skilled professional.  Which I never do, obviously.<P>

   Now leave me alone.  I'm done with this silly debate.<P>

