<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   I do what I'm told, and I've come to prefer it that way most of the time.
Whenever
I'm given creative license on a project, I usually come up with something
unfeasible
in one way or another -- it may be aesthetically inconsistent with
everything else, it
may be technically impractical, etc.  In other words, I tend to "go off."
Just look at
the design, mechanics, and hardware requirements of my web site
(<a href="http://www.milospace.net/">http://www.milospace.net/</a>) versus those of most any other; that should give
you
some idea why I need to be kept reigned in.<P>

   Brad McQuaid *does* tell me to offer my creative input once in a while
(and I did
create two or three monsters, or parts of monsters), but overall, I don't
see a need
for it.  EverQuest is and continues to be a great game with very minimal
artistic input
from me; my duties are very technical, and since I'm technically inclined
anyway, I'm
quite satisfied to work off other artists' designs (mostly Rick Schmitz, who
is highly
skilled and indefatigably creative).<P></td></tr>
